<TITLE> New insurance laws to be tabled Mar 3 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 28 (bdnews24.com)  Two bills on insurance are due to be tabled in parliament on Mar 3, to better regulate the industry and protect customer interests, finance minister AMA Muhith said on Sunday. A cabinet meeting, chaired by prime minister Sheikh Hasina on Mar 30 last year, approved the draft of the Insurance Bill 2009 and Insurance Regulatory Authority (IRA) Bill 2009. If the laws are passed in parliament, the 1938 Insurance Act and the Office of the Chief Controller of Insurance will cease to exist, and the insurance sector will be put under the purview of the proposed IRA. The laws would renew and update Insurance Ordinance 2008 and Insurance Regulatory Authority Ordinance 2008 of the past caretaker government. The draft laws propose a raise in the paid-up capital to Tk 30 crore (300 million) from Tk 7.5 crore for life insurance companies and to Tk 40 crore from Tk 15 crore for general insurance companies. They further proposed increasing statutory deposit to Tk 1.5 crore from Tk 45 lakh for life insurance companies and to Tk 2.5 crore from Tk 90 lakh for general insurance companies. The new laws have made provision for a fund to protect the interest of customers, and allowed insurance companies to form subsidiary firms and run brokerage houses. Under the laws, insurance companies will have fifteen directors of whom eight will come from entrepreneurs, five from the public and two as independent directors. The present provision for the post of a director from insurance policyholders will cease to exist. The insurance regulatory authority will have a chairman and four members for a period of three years and they may be reappointed once onl
